Customer analysis

Introduction

Customer analysis is the visualization of chosen data available online: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/imakash3011/customer-personality-analysis?resource=download The dataset was imported, cleaned up and prepared to analise.

Aim of this report is to support getting answer on below questions:

-What is the correlation between variables?

-What is the purchase volume for customers accordingly to age and children in household?

-Does customers with children purchase more online or off-line?

-Are customers with children more likely to purchase more and more often?

-Are customers with childre more likely to purchase on-line?

Basing on above plots some first insights can be made. The greatest number of customers are around their 50’s and have one children. More customers are in a relationship. Number of customers with one children is visibly higher for those in relationship. The difference for 2 kids in household is not so significant.

Analysis

In this section 4 plots will be presented. The questions to support first business decisions.

-What is the purchase volume for customers accordingly to age and children in household?

-Does customers with children purchase more online or off-line?

-Are customers with children more likely to purchase more and more often?

From this plot it can be seen that customers age mostly is not greater than 80,

but still in late 60/70ties one or two children are leaving in their house.

Despite the fact of household size, purchase volume is in great number of records under 500.

What is interesting, highest purchase volume is not going in line with number of children (the top of plot is showing customers with 0 children mainly).

Last but not least, considering how does this dataset looks like - group of customers with one children are the largest one.

This plot prezents how much of each product was purchased in this database. What was not expected, wine is leading category

of all recorded purchase. Second one is meat, both sweets and fruits on the same level and last position.

This kind of output might suggest that this store is dedicated to some specific product group or it might be kind of “corner shop”,

that is utilized mostly for small shoping for products that are needed “right now”.

Information about the metrics are not available, so that volume of purchase is not giving any actual and meaningfull data. \To ptoceed with better insights data enrichment should be considered.

This chart is confirming last insight from above one - group of customers with one children are the largest one.

Basing on this chart and this dataset it is hard to find one pattern of customer shopping habits.

In general it can be said that excluding several outlayers (customers who highly prefer to purchase on-line) customers shop 50/50 online and off-line.

Number of children in this dataset is not visibly affecting shopping preferences.

Insights from this plot are something I did not expect at all, but the results might be caused by this dataset I am not aware how was collected.

We see that number of children and volume of purchase is in a linear correlation but not the way it might be expected.

What might see strange - customers with greater number of children are purchasing less and not so often as customers with one or no children.

Such situation might be insight reflecting reality but also it can be

Taking into consideration size of the dataset for more valuable insights I would consider if another dataset should be analyzed.

We can see some patterns and relations, but due to fact insights are not matching intuition I would consider how can we improve this dataset and analysis.

I can sum up that cocnlusions that after taking a look on charts might be correct, but in my mind, those should not be driving business.

All in all - this analysis might be a good start for further analysis and data collection.
